 Justification:
 This program, Cartridges P-40A Category AMMUNITION CARTRIDGES Item (A062) CTG, 5.56MM BALL M855 LINKED, is a new start.
 This program, Cartridges P-40A Category AMMUNITION CARTRIDGES Item (A164) CTG, 7.62MM LINKED, is a new start.
 This program, Cartridges P-40A Category AMMUNITION CARTRIDGES Item (A111) CTG 7.62MM BLANK M82 LKD BNDLR, is a new start.
 This program, Cartridges P-40A Category AMMUNITION CARTRIDGES Item (CA20) CTG, 84MM GUN, HEAT 551C RS, CARLGSTF, is a new start.

 Small Caliber Program
 FY2027 amount reflects $27.008 million increase for additional procurement of small caliber ammunition as a result of changing requirements to meet Department priorities.
 FY2027 amounts reflect $5.512 million increase for Great Power Competition.


 MEDIUM CALIBER AMMO:

 Medium Caliber Ammunition funding is essential to sustaining combat capability and training readiness for the F 15, F 16, F 22, F 35A, A 10, and AC 130 fleets. These munitions provide the Air Force's primary
 and alternate combat loads, as well as the training and system verification rounds required for aircrew proficiency and weapons system certification. Each round is platform unique and directly tied to mission
 execution, safety, and maintenance readiness. Continued investment ensures mission success, preserves combat stockpiles, and maintains industrial base stability. Underfunding this portfolio would immediately
 degrade readiness, reduce training throughput, and limit the Air Force's ability to meet operational and contingency demands.

 25MM PGU-48/B (AB98): Required to mitigate an immediate readiness and WRM risk caused by a four year delay in contract award and a current stockpile shortfall of 54 percent of the inventory objective.
 Programmed buys will eventually meet WRM requirements, but any delay to the FY26 award shifts production and deliveries out multiple years, leaving forces exposed in the near term and increasing the
 likelihood of reduced combat readiness, redistribution of limited stocks, and degraded Combatant Command (COCOM) support globally.


 SMALL CALIBER/GROUND MUNITIONS:

 The Air Force requires the procurement of Small Caliber Ammunition to sustain operational readiness, training proficiency, and mission execution for Active Duty, Guard, and Reserve components, with
 procurement conducted primarily through the Single Manager for Conventional Ammunition (SMCA), Department of the Army, except for 9mm Frangible (AA16) and 5.56mm Special Ball (AA53), which are
 procured through the Department of the Navy. These munitions are essential to maintaining appropriate quantities within War Reserve Materiel (WRM) munitions stockpiles and supporting annual test and
 training allocations based on current-year requirements; failure to procure these items risks degradation of WRM posture and the Air Force's ability to meet operational and training demands. The ammunition
 portfolio includes live, blank, frangible, marking, tracer, and target practice rounds across multiple calibers (5.56mm, 7.62mm, 9mm, .50 caliber, 40mm, and 84mm) to support 740 weapons systems including
 pistols, rifles, squad automatic weapons, machine guns, grenade launchers, and recoilless rifles, enabling realistic, safe, and effective training as well as combat capability.

