 Justification:
 Title 10 of the Code of Federal Regulations, Part 20 (10 CFR 20) requires RADIAC instruments be used to ensure the safety of personnel who work with or who are exposed to radioactive materials in their work.
 This request supports the Department of Defense National Defense Strategy objective in the areas of Human Health and Safety, by providing equipment that enables the safe and legally compliant operation
 of the U.S. Navy's nuclear reactors; industrial and research uses of radiation, medical radiation applications; monitoring of nuclear weapons; detection of radiological Weapons of Mass Destruction (WMD); and
 continuity of operations in the event of a radiological or nuclear incident.

 The U.S. Navy's mission requires personnel and ships to have the ability to operate in radiological environments and the ability to identify and interdict radiological WMD. U.S. Navy programs that require RADIAC
 instruments for Occupational Safety & Health (OSH) reasons under the provisions of 10 CFR 20 include Naval Nuclear Propulsion, Nuclear Weapons, Medical, and Radiological Affairs Support. Non-OSH
 programs include Radiological Defense, Consequence Management, Training, Technical (RADIAC calibration, shielding evaluation, research) and Radiological Search (maritime interdiction to locate or intercept
 WMD).

 The funding increase from FY26 to FY27 supports procurement of dosimetry systems necessary to meet mission requirements. Purchasing the required quantity in FY27 allows the program to achieve lower unit
 costs through bulk procurement and supports timely fielding of the capability.




