 Description:
 The C-5M carries outsized and heavy cargo (tanks, helicopters, etc.) between main operating bases. Additionally, the aircraft is capable of carrying 73 troops and 36 standard 463-L pallets. There are 52 C-5
 aircraft in the Air Force fleet. The fleet was delivered to the Air Force between 1969 and 1989. Service life was extended to 2040 as a result of the reliability enhancement and re-engining program (RERP)
 modification.

 Current programs include C-5M Replacement Multi-function Capability Display (RMCD), Mission Systems Equipment-Lavatory (MSE-Lav), C-5M Embedded Diagnostics System-II (EDS II) and Low Cost
 Modifications (Capability Improvement).

 Activities in support of these programs and DMS include studies and analyses, life-of-type buys, risk reduction efforts, engineering change orders, and other government costs such as travel, program support,
 government furnished equipment (GFE), and over and above costs.

 In accordance with Section 1815 of the FY 2008 National Defense Authorization Act (P.L.110-181), this item is necessary for use by the active and reserve components of the Armed Forces for homeland
 defense missions, domestic emergency responses, and providing military support to civil authorities.

 These modifications support performance of a full financial audit as required by title 10 U.S.C. Chapter 9A, Sec 240-D.

 Funding for this exhibit is contained in PE 0401119F and 0401897F.
